& Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Digital breast tomosynthesis (DBT) has been widely adopted in breast imaging in both screening and diagnostic settings. The benefits of DBT are well established. Compared with two-dimensional digital mammography (DM), DBT preferentially increases detection of invasive cancers without increased detection of in-situ cancers, maximizing identification of biologically significant disease, while mitigating overdiagnosis. The higher sensitivity of DBT for architectural distortion allows increased diagnosis of invasive cancers overall and particularly improves the visibility of invasive lobular cancers. Implementation of DBT has decreased the number of recalls for false-positive findings at screening, contributing to improved specificity at diagnostic evaluation. Integration of DBT in diagnostic examinations has also resulted in an increased percentage of biopsies with positive results, improving diagnostic confidence. Although individual DBT examinations have a longer interpretation time compared with that for DM, DBT has streamlined the diagnostic workflow and minimized the need for short-term follow-up examinations, redistributing much-needed time resources to screening. Yet DBT has limitations. Although improvements in cancer detection and recall rates are seen for patients in a large spectrum of age groups and breast density categories, these benefits are minimal in women with extremely dense breast tissue, and the extent of these benefits may vary by practice environment and by geographic location. Although DBT allows detection of more invasive cancers than does DM, its incremental yield is lower than that of US and MRI. Current understanding of the biologic profile of DBT-detected cancers is limited. Whether DBT improves breast cancer–specific mortality remains a key question that requires further investigation.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2021</div></section><section id="graphical-abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Visual Abstract</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="_i1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/rg.2021200101.va.png" height="720" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=_i1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figure></div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200101">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2021200101">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic" aria-label="Screening-detected grade 1 node-negative estrogen receptor positive (ER+), progesterone receptor positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 negative (HER2−) breast cancer in a 44-year-old woman. (a) Two-dimensional mammogram shows that the cancer is obscured. (b) Mediolateral oblique projection in-plane DBT image clearly shows the cancer (arrow), with improved lesion conspicuity and depiction of tumor margins."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig1a.jpeg" height="1456" width="1255" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Screening-detected grade 1 node-negative estrogen receptor positive (ER+), progesterone receptor positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 negative (HER2−) breast cancer in a 44-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional mammogram shows that the cancer is obscured. <b>(b)</b> Mediolateral oblique projection in-plane DBT image clearly shows the cancer (arrow), with improved lesion conspicuity and depiction of tumor margins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic" aria-label="Screening-detected grade 1 node-negative estrogen receptor positive (ER+), progesterone receptor positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 negative (HER2−) breast cancer in a 44-year-old woman. (a) Two-dimensional mammogram shows that the cancer is obscured. (b) Mediolateral oblique projection in-plane DBT image clearly shows the cancer (arrow), with improved lesion conspicuity and depiction of tumor margins."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig1b.jpeg" height="1454" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Screening-detected grade 1 node-negative estrogen receptor positive (ER+), progesterone receptor positive (PR+) human epidermal growth factor receptor 2 negative (HER2−) breast cancer in a 44-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Two-dimensional mammogram shows that the cancer is obscured. <b>(b)</b> Mediolateral oblique projection in-plane DBT image clearly shows the cancer (arrow), with improved lesion conspicuity and depiction of tumor margins.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic" aria-label="Images show distinct visual representations of the logarithm of two-dimensional noise power spectra calculated from the center of the reconstructed plane for each studied DBT system. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference 105.)"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig2.jpeg" height="2622" width="3758" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Images show distinct visual representations of the logarithm of two-dimensional noise power spectra calculated from the center of the reconstructed plane for each studied DBT system. (Reprinted, with permission, from reference <a href="#r105" role="doc-biblioref" data-xml-rid="r105">105</a>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram (a), synthetic C-view image (b), and in-plane DBT image (c) of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig3a.jpeg" height="1977" width="958" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b>, synthetic C-view image <b>(b)</b>, and in-plane DBT image <b>(c)</b> of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram (a), synthetic C-view image (b), and in-plane DBT image (c) of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig3b.jpeg" height="1977" width="952" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b>, synthetic C-view image <b>(b)</b>, and in-plane DBT image <b>(c)</b> of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram (a), synthetic C-view image (b), and in-plane DBT image (c) of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig3c.jpeg" height="1977" width="991" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Images from the Hologic Dimensions DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2011. Mediolateral oblique two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b>, synthetic C-view image <b>(b)</b>, and in-plane DBT image <b>(c)</b> of the left breast in a 40-year-old woman at baseline screening show diagnostic-quality images of a small spiculated mass (arrow) that was biopsy proven to be a grade 1 ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional (a), synthetic V-preview (b), and DBT (c) images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig4a.jpeg" height="1994" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional <b>(a)</b>, synthetic V-preview <b>(b)</b>, and DBT <b>(c)</b> images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional (a), synthetic V-preview (b), and DBT (c) images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig4b.jpeg" height="1993" width="967" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional <b>(a)</b>, synthetic V-preview <b>(b)</b>, and DBT <b>(c)</b> images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional (a), synthetic V-preview (b), and DBT (c) images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig4c.jpeg" height="1993" width="990" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Images from the GE SenoClaire DBT system, which was approved by the FDA in 2014. Mediolateral oblique diagnostic-quality two-dimensional <b>(a)</b>, synthetic V-preview <b>(b)</b>, and DBT <b>(c)</b> images of the right breast in a 78-year-old woman at diagnostic imaging show an irregular mass in the inferior breast (arrow), which is consistent with a biopsy proven ER+/PR+/HER2− invasive lobular carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic" aria-label="Images from the Siemens Mammomat Inspiration system, which was FDA approved in 2015. Mediolateral oblique DBT images at various depths through a normal left breast in a 50-year-old woman at a screening examination show diagnostic image quality."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig5a.jpeg" height="1928" width="962" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig5b.jpeg" height="1928" width="964" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig5c.jpeg" height="1928" width="970" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5</span>. Images from the Siemens Mammomat Inspiration system, which was FDA approved in 2015. Mediolateral oblique DBT images at various depths through a normal left breast in a 50-year-old woman at a screening examination show diagnostic image quality.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic" aria-label="Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. (a, b) Mediolateral oblique (a) and craniocaudal (b) two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. (c) In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig6a.jpeg" height="2223" width="926" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. <b>(c)</b> In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic" aria-label="Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. (a, b) Mediolateral oblique (a) and craniocaudal (b) two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. (c) In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig6b.jpeg" height="2222" width="969" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. <b>(c)</b> In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic" aria-label="Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. (a, b) Mediolateral oblique (a) and craniocaudal (b) two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. (c) In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig6c.jpeg" height="2223" width="1004" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span>. Small spiculated grade 1 node-negative ER+/PR+/HER2−invasive ductal carcinoma in a 62-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Mediolateral oblique <b>(a)</b> and craniocaudal <b>(b)</b> two-dimensional mammograms show that the tumor is occult. <b>(c)</b> In-plane craniocaudal DBT image shows that the tumor is visible (arrow), but it is occult on other DBT views (not shown). Note that cancers may be better seen or only seen in one projection at DBT because of nonisotropic imaging; therefore, findings suspected to be cancer on only one DBT view require complete workup.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic" aria-label="Juxtaposition of mediolateral oblique views of the left breast in two separate patients. High-resolution (70-µm pixel size) (a) and standard-resolution (140-µm pixel size) (b) SM images show that glandular details are seen to greater advantage on a than on b. High-resolution acquisition may compensate for the loss of resolution on SM images but is associated with a slightly higher dose of radiation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig7a.jpeg" height="2073" width="1022" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Juxtaposition of mediolateral oblique views of the left breast in two separate patients. High-resolution (70-µm pixel size) <b>(a)</b> and standard-resolution (140-µm pixel size) <b>(b)</b> SM images show that glandular details are seen to greater advantage on <b>a</b> than on <b>b</b>. High-resolution acquisition may compensate for the loss of resolution on SM images but is associated with a slightly higher dose of radiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic" aria-label="Juxtaposition of mediolateral oblique views of the left breast in two separate patients. High-resolution (70-µm pixel size) (a) and standard-resolution (140-µm pixel size) (b) SM images show that glandular details are seen to greater advantage on a than on b. High-resolution acquisition may compensate for the loss of resolution on SM images but is associated with a slightly higher dose of radiation."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig7b.jpeg" height="2074" width="1028" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Juxtaposition of mediolateral oblique views of the left breast in two separate patients. High-resolution (70-µm pixel size) <b>(a)</b> and standard-resolution (140-µm pixel size) <b>(b)</b> SM images show that glandular details are seen to greater advantage on <b>a</b> than on <b>b</b>. High-resolution acquisition may compensate for the loss of resolution on SM images but is associated with a slightly higher dose of radiation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic" aria-label="High-resolution DBT (a) and SM (b) images in mediolateral oblique projection of the left breast in a 45-year-old woman show excellent image quality because of improved resolution (70-µm pixel size). There are scattered punctate microcalcifications in the left breast, shown with great clarity and without significant artifacts on b (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig8a.jpeg" height="1729" width="1030" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. High-resolution DBT <b>(a)</b> and SM <b>(b)</b> images in mediolateral oblique projection of the left breast in a 45-year-old woman show excellent image quality because of improved resolution (70-µm pixel size). There are scattered punctate microcalcifications in the left breast, shown with great clarity and without significant artifacts on <b>b</b> (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic" aria-label="High-resolution DBT (a) and SM (b) images in mediolateral oblique projection of the left breast in a 45-year-old woman show excellent image quality because of improved resolution (70-µm pixel size). There are scattered punctate microcalcifications in the left breast, shown with great clarity and without significant artifacts on b (arrows)."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig8b.jpeg" height="1729" width="1017" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. High-resolution DBT <b>(a)</b> and SM <b>(b)</b> images in mediolateral oblique projection of the left breast in a 45-year-old woman show excellent image quality because of improved resolution (70-µm pixel size). There are scattered punctate microcalcifications in the left breast, shown with great clarity and without significant artifacts on <b>b</b> (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic" aria-label="High-grade ductal carcinoma in situ at baseline screening in a 40-year-old woman. Mediolateral oblique in-plane DBT (a) and 10-mm slab (b) images show segmentally distributed fine linear branching calcifications in the left breast (solid arrows). Currently the standard section thickness for DBT reconstruction images is 1 mm. Slab viewing is possible (dashed arrow in b) with adjustable slab thickness to allow quicker review. In this patient, slab viewing also allows a maximum intensity projection–like capture of the overall extent of the abnormality. Stereotactic biopsy was performed and yielded a diagnosis of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig9a.jpeg" height="2393" width="1019" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. High-grade ductal carcinoma in situ at baseline screening in a 40-year-old woman. Mediolateral oblique in-plane DBT <b>(a)</b> and 10-mm slab <b>(b)</b> images show segmentally distributed fine linear branching calcifications in the left breast (solid arrows). Currently the standard section thickness for DBT reconstruction images is 1 mm. Slab viewing is possible (dashed arrow in <b>b</b>) with adjustable slab thickness to allow quicker review. In this patient, slab viewing also allows a maximum intensity projection–like capture of the overall extent of the abnormality. Stereotactic biopsy was performed and yielded a diagnosis of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic" aria-label="High-grade ductal carcinoma in situ at baseline screening in a 40-year-old woman. Mediolateral oblique in-plane DBT (a) and 10-mm slab (b) images show segmentally distributed fine linear branching calcifications in the left breast (solid arrows). Currently the standard section thickness for DBT reconstruction images is 1 mm. Slab viewing is possible (dashed arrow in b) with adjustable slab thickness to allow quicker review. In this patient, slab viewing also allows a maximum intensity projection–like capture of the overall extent of the abnormality. Stereotactic biopsy was performed and yielded a diagnosis of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig9b.jpeg" height="2392" width="1029" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. High-grade ductal carcinoma in situ at baseline screening in a 40-year-old woman. Mediolateral oblique in-plane DBT <b>(a)</b> and 10-mm slab <b>(b)</b> images show segmentally distributed fine linear branching calcifications in the left breast (solid arrows). Currently the standard section thickness for DBT reconstruction images is 1 mm. Slab viewing is possible (dashed arrow in <b>b</b>) with adjustable slab thickness to allow quicker review. In this patient, slab viewing also allows a maximum intensity projection–like capture of the overall extent of the abnormality. Stereotactic biopsy was performed and yielded a diagnosis of high-grade ductal carcinoma in situ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic" aria-label="Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. (a, b) Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram (a) and in-plane DBT image (b) show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). (c) Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig10a.jpeg" height="1272" width="1282" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b> and in-plane DBT image <b>(b)</b> show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic" aria-label="Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. (a, b) Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram (a) and in-plane DBT image (b) show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). (c) Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig10b.jpeg" height="1272" width="1278" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b> and in-plane DBT image <b>(b)</b> show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic" aria-label="Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. (a, b) Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram (a) and in-plane DBT image (b) show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). (c) Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma."><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2021200101/asset/images/large/rg.2021200101.fig10c.jpeg" height="1271" width="1147" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma in a 56-year-old woman at screening mammography. <b>(a, b)</b> Craniocaudal projection two-dimensional mammogram <b>(a)</b> and in-plane DBT image <b>(b)</b> show scattered fibroglandular tissue and a circumscribed solitary right breast mass (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Subsequent US image shows a corresponding mass with irregular borders (arrow). Biopsy was performed and yielded a grade 2 ER+/PR+/HER2+ node-negative invasive ductal carcinoma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2021200101&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Lowry KP, Coley RY, Miglioretti DL, et al. Screening performance of digital breast tomosynthesis vs digital mammography in community practice by patient age, screening round, and breast density. <em>JAMA Netw Open</em> 2020;3(7):e2011792.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1001/jamanetworkopen.2020.11792">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32721031/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Screening+performance+of+digital+breast+tomosynthesis+vs+digital+mammography+in+community+practice+by+patient+age%2C+screening+round%2C+and+breast+density&amp;author=KP+Lowry&amp;author=RY+Coley&amp;author=DL+Miglioretti&amp;publication_year=2020&amp;journal=JAMA+Netw+Open&amp;pages=e2011792&amp;doi=10.1001%2Fjamanetworkopen.2020.11792&amp;pmid=32721031">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Hovda T, Holen ÅS, Lâng K, et al. Interval and consecutive round breast cancer after digital breast tomosynthesis and synthetic 2D mammography versus standard 2D digital mammography in BreastScreen Norway. <em>Radiology</em> 2020;294(2):256–264.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-cross